[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1544},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fvue\u002F2025\u002F11\u002F06\u002Fvue-sfc-spec-block-for-ai-development\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fvue\u002F2025\u002F11\u002F06\u002Fvue-sfc-spec-block-for-ai-development\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fvue\u002F2025\u002F11\u002F06\u002Fvue-sfc-spec-block-for-ai-development\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fvue\u002F2025\u002F11\u002F06\u002Fvue-sfc-spec-block-for-ai-development\u002F":1520,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fvue\u002F2025\u002F11\u002F06\u002Fvue-sfc-spec-block-for-ai-development\u002F":1529},"\u002Fvue\u002F20251106\u002F1172686218\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1501,"date":1502,"description":1503,"extension":1504,"lang":1505,"meta":1506,"navigation":174,"path":1507,"readingMinutes":1508,"seo":1509,"standalone":1510,"stem":1511,"tags":1512,"tldr":1516,"updated":1517,"url":1518,"__hash__":1519},"content\u002Fen\u002FVue\u002Fvue-sfc-spec-block-for-ai-development.md","Use a Custom &lt;spec lang=\"md\"&gt; Block in Vue SFC for Smoother AI Development","7611862812",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1489},"minimark",[11,19,24,32,36,39,52,55,63,66,69,72,89,92,95,98,101,108,123,365,371,377,388,391,645,648,704,710,713,1010,1013,1185,1191,1194,1214,1221,1226,1241,1331,1337,1341,1344,1357,1363,1370,1373,1377,1380,1404,1410,1419,1422,1437,1441,1447,1450,1453,1457,1486],[12,13,14],"p",{},[15,16],"img",{"alt":17,"src":18},"Use a custom \u003Cspec lang=\"md\"> block in Vue SFC for smoother AI development","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002Fblog\u002Fvue\u002Fai-spec-tag\u002FGemini_Generated_Image_85e8id85e8id85e8_1280x714.png",[20,21,23],"h2",{"id":22},"intro","Intro",[12,25,26,27,31],{},"Lots of devs pair AI tools (Claude Code, Gemini, Copilot, etc.) with their workflow, and Vue Single File Components (SFC) tend to hit some friction along the way. So here's a different approach — adding a custom ",[28,29,30],"code",{},"\u003Cspec lang=\"md\">"," block so you can use AI tools in SFC with way less hassle.",[20,33,35],{"id":34},"ai-development-modes","AI development modes",[12,37,38],{},"There are basically three modes of AI-assisted development right now:",[40,41,42,46,49],"ul",{},[43,44,45],"li",{},"SDD (Specification Driven Development): write the spec first, then let AI generate code from it.",[43,47,48],{},"BDD (Behavior Driven Development): write the behavior description first, then let AI generate code from it.",[43,50,51],{},"TDD (Test Driven Development): write the tests first, then let AI generate code from them.",[12,53,54],{},"SDD is the most popular of the three. As long as you describe the spec clearly, AI can produce code that matches your requirements. I won't go deep into how to use or write SDD here though.",[12,56,57,58,62],{},"But here's the thing — what does ",[59,60,61],"strong",{},"\"describe the spec clearly\""," actually mean?",[12,64,65],{},"Honestly I find this interesting. Describing your own problem clearly is already hard enough, let alone the fact that AI only generates code based on what you actually say and provide. On top of that, there's no real standard for measuring whether your description is clear enough or what it should include.",[12,67,68],{},"Usually before we ask AI to write code, we'll have it do a preliminary project analysis and generate a project spec doc. The next time we open the project and ask AI to write code, we just feed this spec doc back to AI and let it work from there.",[12,70,71],{},"So you end up with a pile of docs like:",[40,73,74,77,80,83,86],{},[43,75,76],{},"*.spec.md: project spec doc",[43,78,79],{},"*.test.md: test case doc",[43,81,82],{},"*.guide.md: development guide",[43,84,85],{},"*.task.md: task list",[43,87,88],{},"README.md: project readme\n...",[12,90,91],{},"And so on — sometimes you'll even split out code samples into separate docs to explain.",[12,93,94],{},"As you can imagine, dev docs pile up fast, and you have to keep updating them so they stay in sync with the code\u002Frequirements.",[12,96,97],{},"You might think \"these docs are just for the AI anyway, no big deal\", but they actually slow down development too — you have to spend time maintaining them. You can't just ignore them and ask AI to write code blindly.",[12,99,100],{},"Not to mention AI Context Windows are limited.",[20,102,104,105,107],{"id":103},"using-spec-langmd-in-vue-sfc","Using ",[28,106,30],{}," in Vue SFC",[12,109,110,111,114,115,118,119,122],{},"In Vue SFC, we already have ",[28,112,113],{},"\u003Ctemplate>",", ",[28,116,117],{},"\u003Cscript>",", and ",[28,120,121],{},"\u003Cstyle>"," blocks for templates, logic, and styles. But Vue also supports custom blocks, and we can use this feature to add our spec doc. After wiring it up, it looks something like this:",[124,125,130],"pre",{"className":126,"code":127,"language":128,"meta":129,"style":129},"language-html shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","\u003Cscript setup>\nimport { ref } from 'vue'\n\nconst message = ref('Hello World')\n\u003C\u002Fscript>\n\n\u003Ctemplate>\n  \u003Cdiv>{{ message }}\u003C\u002Fdiv>\n\u003C\u002Ftemplate>\n\n\u003Cstyle scoped>\ndiv {\n  color: blue;\n}\n\u003C\u002Fstyle>\n\n\u003Cspec lang=\"md\">\n- A simple Vue component that shows a blue \"Hello World\" message.\n- Uses Vue 3 Composition API to define the reactive variable `message`.\n- The style uses scoped so it only applies to this component.\n- The text color of `message` is set to blue.\n\u003C\u002Fspec>\n","html","",[28,131,132,152,169,176,201,211,216,226,242,251,256,269,277,292,298,307,312,332,338,344,350,356],{"__ignoreMap":129},[133,134,137,141,145,149],"span",{"class":135,"line":136},"line",1,[133,138,140],{"class":139},"sMAXC","\u003C",[133,142,144],{"class":143},"sKpQp","script",[133,146,148],{"class":147},"sCcAr"," setup",[133,150,151],{"class":139},">\n",[133,153,155,159,162,165],{"class":135,"line":154},2,[133,156,158],{"class":157},"sWyjQ","import",[133,160,161],{"class":139}," { ref } ",[133,163,164],{"class":157},"from",[133,166,168],{"class":167},"sTRMh"," 'vue'\n",[133,170,172],{"class":135,"line":171},3,[133,173,175],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":174},true,"\n",[133,177,179,182,185,188,192,195,198],{"class":135,"line":178},4,[133,180,181],{"class":157},"const",[133,183,184],{"class":147}," message",[133,186,187],{"class":157}," =",[133,189,191],{"class":190},"sj_SG"," ref",[133,193,194],{"class":139},"(",[133,196,197],{"class":167},"'Hello World'",[133,199,200],{"class":139},")\n",[133,202,204,207,209],{"class":135,"line":203},5,[133,205,206],{"class":139},"\u003C\u002F",[133,208,144],{"class":143},[133,210,151],{"class":139},[133,212,214],{"class":135,"line":213},6,[133,215,175],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":174},[133,217,219,221,224],{"class":135,"line":218},7,[133,220,140],{"class":139},[133,222,223],{"class":143},"template",[133,225,151],{"class":139},[133,227,229,232,235,238,240],{"class":135,"line":228},8,[133,230,231],{"class":139},"  \u003C",[133,233,234],{"class":143},"div",[133,236,237],{"class":139},">{{ message }}\u003C\u002F",[133,239,234],{"class":143},[133,241,151],{"class":139},[133,243,245,247,249],{"class":135,"line":244},9,[133,246,206],{"class":139},[133,248,223],{"class":143},[133,250,151],{"class":139},[133,252,254],{"class":135,"line":253},10,[133,255,175],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":174},[133,257,259,261,264,267],{"class":135,"line":258},11,[133,260,140],{"class":139},[133,262,263],{"class":143},"style",[133,265,266],{"class":147}," scoped",[133,268,151],{"class":139},[133,270,272,274],{"class":135,"line":271},12,[133,273,234],{"class":143},[133,275,276],{"class":139}," {\n",[133,278,280,283,286,289],{"class":135,"line":279},13,[133,281,282],{"class":147},"  color",[133,284,285],{"class":139},": ",[133,287,288],{"class":147},"blue",[133,290,291],{"class":139},";\n",[133,293,295],{"class":135,"line":294},14,[133,296,297],{"class":139},"}\n",[133,299,301,303,305],{"class":135,"line":300},15,[133,302,206],{"class":139},[133,304,263],{"class":143},[133,306,151],{"class":139},[133,308,310],{"class":135,"line":309},16,[133,311,175],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":174},[133,313,315,317,321,324,327,330],{"class":135,"line":314},17,[133,316,140],{"class":139},[133,318,320],{"class":319},"szH_Z","spec",[133,322,323],{"class":147}," lang",[133,325,326],{"class":139},"=",[133,328,329],{"class":167},"\"md\"",[133,331,151],{"class":139},[133,333,335],{"class":135,"line":334},18,[133,336,337],{"class":139},"- A simple Vue component that shows a blue \"Hello World\" message.\n",[133,339,341],{"class":135,"line":340},19,[133,342,343],{"class":139},"- Uses Vue 3 Composition API to define the reactive variable `message`.\n",[133,345,347],{"class":135,"line":346},20,[133,348,349],{"class":139},"- The style uses scoped so it only applies to this component.\n",[133,351,353],{"class":135,"line":352},21,[133,354,355],{"class":139},"- The text color of `message` is set to blue.\n",[133,357,359,361,363],{"class":135,"line":358},22,[133,360,206],{"class":139},[133,362,320],{"class":319},[133,364,151],{"class":139},[12,366,367],{},[15,368],{"alt":369,"src":370},"Before","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002Fblog\u002Fvue\u002Fvue-spec-plugin\u002F20251106142007.png",[12,372,373],{},[15,374],{"alt":375,"src":376},"After","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002Fblog\u002Fvue\u002Fvue-spec-plugin\u002F20251106142014.png",[12,378,379,380,387],{},"So how do you actually pull this off? The official docs cover how to use custom blocks — check out ",[381,382,386],"a",{"href":383,"rel":384},"https:\u002F\u002Fvuejs.org\u002Fguide\u002Fscaling-up\u002Ftooling.html#sfc-custom-block-integrations",[385],"nofollow","SFC Custom Block Integrations",".",[12,389,390],{},"The doc has an i18n custom block example:",[124,392,396],{"className":393,"code":394,"language":395,"meta":129,"style":129},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","import vue from '@vitejs\u002Fplugin-vue'\nimport yaml from 'js-yaml'\n\nconst vueI18nPlugin = {\n  name: 'vue-i18n',\n  transform(code, id) {\n    \u002F\u002F if .vue file don't have \u003Ci18n> block, just return\n    if (!\u002Fvue&type=i18n\u002F.test(id)) {\n      return\n    }\n    \u002F\u002F parse yaml\n    if (\u002F\\.ya?ml$\u002F.test(id)) {\n      code = JSON.stringify(yaml.load(code.trim()))\n    }\n    \u002F\u002F mount the value on the i18n property of the component instance\n    return `export default Comp => {\n      Comp.i18n = ${code}\n    }`\n  },\n}\n\nexport default {\n  plugins: [vue(), vueI18nPlugin],\n}\n","js",[28,397,398,410,422,426,437,448,466,472,494,499,504,509,542,572,576,581,589,598,603,608,612,616,626,640],{"__ignoreMap":129},[133,399,400,402,405,407],{"class":135,"line":136},[133,401,158],{"class":157},[133,403,404],{"class":139}," vue ",[133,406,164],{"class":157},[133,408,409],{"class":167}," '@vitejs\u002Fplugin-vue'\n",[133,411,412,414,417,419],{"class":135,"line":154},[133,413,158],{"class":157},[133,415,416],{"class":139}," yaml ",[133,418,164],{"class":157},[133,420,421],{"class":167}," 'js-yaml'\n",[133,423,424],{"class":135,"line":171},[133,425,175],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":174},[133,427,428,430,433,435],{"class":135,"line":178},[133,429,181],{"class":157},[133,431,432],{"class":147}," vueI18nPlugin",[133,434,187],{"class":157},[133,436,276],{"class":139},[133,438,439,442,445],{"class":135,"line":203},[133,440,441],{"class":139},"  name: ",[133,443,444],{"class":167},"'vue-i18n'",[133,446,447],{"class":139},",\n",[133,449,450,453,455,458,460,463],{"class":135,"line":213},[133,451,452],{"class":190},"  transform",[133,454,194],{"class":139},[133,456,28],{"class":457},"s_sBn",[133,459,114],{"class":139},[133,461,462],{"class":457},"id",[133,464,465],{"class":139},") {\n",[133,467,468],{"class":135,"line":218},[133,469,471],{"class":470},"sQrFR","    \u002F\u002F if .vue file don't have \u003Ci18n> block, just return\n",[133,473,474,477,480,483,486,488,491],{"class":13